SIMPLE: hope
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hope
<hw>Hope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel.
<ets>h⟦omac⟧p</ets> a small bay or inlet.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
sloping plain between mountain ridges.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small bay; an inlet; a haven.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark> <rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hope</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hope
<hw>Hope</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS., <ets>akin to D</ets>.
<ets>hoop</ets>, <ets>hope</ets>, Sw. <ets>hopp</ets>, Dan.
<ets>haab</ets>, MHG. <ets>hoffe</ets>. <ets>Hope</ets> in <ets>forlorn
hope</ets> is different word. See <ets>Forlorn hope</ets>, under
<er>Forlorn</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A desire of some good,
accompanied with an expectation of obtaining it, or a belief that it is
obtainable; an expectation of something which is thought to be
desirable; confidence; pleasing expectancy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hypocrite's <qex>hope</qex> shall perish.</q> <rj><qau>Job
vii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wished, but not with <qex>hope</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>New thoughts of God, new <qex>hopes</qex> of Heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, gives hope, furnishes ground
of expectation, or promises desired good.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord will be the <qex>hope</qex> of his people.</q>
<rj><qau>Joel iii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A young gentleman of great <qex>hopes</qex>, whose love of
learning was highly commendable.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is hoped for; an object of
hope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lavina is thine elder brother's <qex>hope</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hope</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hope
<hw>Hope</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hoped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hoping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>hopian</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>hopen</ets>, Sw. <ets>hoppan</ets>, Dan. <ets>haabe</ets>, G.
<ets>hoffen</ets>. See 2nd <er>Hope</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
entertain or indulge hope; to cherish a desire of good, or of something
welcome, with expectation of obtaining it or belief that it is
obtainable; to expect; -- usually followed by <xex>for</xex>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hope</xex> for good success.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Jer.
Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But I will <qex>hope</qex> continually.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxxi.
14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To place confidence; to trust with confident
expectation of good; -- usually followed by <xex>in</xex>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>hope</xex> in thy word.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ps. cxix.
81.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why art thou cast down, O my soul? and why art thou disquieted
within me? <qex>Hope</qex> thou in God.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xlii.
11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 705 --></p>

<p><ent>Hope</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hope
<hw>Hope</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
desire with expectation or with belief in the possibility or prospect of
obtaining; to look forward to as a thing desirable, with the expectation
of obtaining it; to cherish hopes of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>hope</qex> no other from your majesty.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Charity] <qex>hopeth</qex> all things.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. xiii.
7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To expect; to fear.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>hope</xex> he will be dead.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Hope</xex> is often used colloquially regarding
uncertainties, with no reference to the future. ⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>hope</xex>
she takes me to be flesh and blood.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Mrs.
Centlivre.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hoped-for</ent>⟦br⟧
